    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-10-15T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-10-15T16:00:00-05:00" n="300"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d300">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.77/187</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Russia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_FDR1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Francis</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-10-15T16:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 15, 1917, 4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1775. Your 1821, September 29. <persName corresp="#p_WD1">Willard</persName>
                    replies: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>Unable to send at once high railroad officer of kind you request.
                                <persName corresp="#p_SJF1">Stevens</persName> is considered one of
                            the ablest railroad engineers in this country. It is suggested that he
                            act as adviser to Minister of Means of Communication in Petrograd, and
                            let <persName>Miller</persName> look after operations on Trans-Siberian
                            which he is thoroughly competent to do. <persName corresp="#p_ECH1"
                                >George Emerson</persName>, general manager, Great Northern
                            Railroad, will leave for Vladivostok in about three weeks with force of
                            300 American railroad officers and skilled mechanics. They will give <pb
                                facs="0253" n="203" xml:id="pg_203"/>
                            <persName>Miller</persName> the support he needs on Trans-Siberian. I
                            recommend above arrangement and feel certain no better selection than
                                <persName corresp="#p_SJF1">Stevens</persName> could be made for
                            particular place or duties you have in mind in Petrograd. Advise if this
                            arrangement will be satisfactory.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Department concurs.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
